{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b16d3e8-f4d9-458e-80ba-d471b3ca6000","content":"You don't need the SDK. Install `dotnet-trace` as a **global tool** using just the runtime, or grab the standalone binary:\n\n**Option 1 — .NET global tool (needs SDK or tool manifest):**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Standalone download (no SDK required):**\n```bash\n# Download the self-contained version directly into the container\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Then collect the CPU trace:**\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis downloads a single native binary with no SDK dependency. Once done, copy the `.nettrace` file out of the container (`docker cp`) and open it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aebc21cc-77c7-4e23-9457-b8a50d603231","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Linux container without the .NET SDK. This is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling - specifically about getting `dotnet-trace` into a container that only has the .NET runtime (not the SDK).\n\nLet me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"980B:11A36E:CD33AE:EE79A6:69F40241"},"id":"599ade5c-a60f-44c7-8891-79b1dee12e3b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:49.468Z","parentId":"55c8e5e2-7e7f-4fd5-bf85-4223e0c440de"}
